commit.message:
Added haversine_vector

Added second version of haversine function that uses vectorized numpy functions (instead of scalar math library functions).

Remove map() call (#27)

Avoid the overhead of constructing the tuple, map object, and deconstructing it:

```
In [1]: from math import radians

In [2]: a = b = c = d = 1.0

In [3]: %timeit ar, br, cr, dr = map(radians, (a, b, c, d))
427 ns ± 1.54 ns per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1000000 loops each)

In [4]: %timeit ar = radians(a) ; br = radians(b) ; cr = radians(c) ; dr = radians(d)
271 ns ± 1.79 ns per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1000000 loops each)
```

Whilst a micro-optimization, `haversine()` is often called on large data sets so this can lead to an overall large speedup.

commit.message:
Quick fix (#23)

* fix: programmatic acces to enum

* refactor: rename to `Unit`

General refactor: use Enum for available units, extract constants (#22)

* refactor: use Enum for available units, extract constants

Made an enumeration for supported units for greater maintainability
(`class Units(enum.Enum)`).

Also, constants have been extracted outside the function, to
avoid having to re-construct them each time, with a leading underscore
(so that `from haversine import *` only imports `haversine`
and `Units`).

* docs: update docs and format in reST

* tests: refactored tests into a common pattern, added Unit enum test

* chore: add `enum34` install requirement

* docs: updated README

* chore: specify Python version in `install_requires`

A simplify way of changing measurement units (#20)

* moves haversine function to its own file which is refered in __init__

* adds new unit API

* Updates old new unit tests for the new API

* Updates docstring

* Remove old function parameters in the examples, add the new ones
use better precision in README file
